<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
In a statement on behalf of the European Union, the head of EU diplomacy denounced the fact that LGTBI people “continue to be target of violence, discrimination and stigmatization”, at a time of “wonderful arrests and retreats on a global scale”. He also encouraged action to remove obstacles and “structural prejudices” which limit the participation of LGTBIQ+ people in political and decision-making processes.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
According to the study “LGBTIQ equality at a crossroads: progress and challenges” (LGBTIQ equality at a crossroads: progress and challenges), published this week by the European Union Agency for Fundamental Rights (FRA), more and more LGBTIQ+ people declare themselves openly but at the same time face more violence, harassment and bullying than ever.
The report, conducted on more than 100,000 people in the 27 EU countries plus Albania, northern Macedonia and Serbia, shows that more than one out of three people suffer discrimination in daily life, a slight decline compared to two out of five in 2019, but states that discrimination remains invisible, since only one out of ten people denounce accidents.&nbsp;
